  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions traces back several decades, with key developments occurring in different stages:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Initial anti-money laundering (AML) efforts emerged in the United States during the 1970s\n- Bank Secrecy Act of 1970 was the first significant legislation requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n\n2. International Development:\n- 1980s saw growing international recognition of money laundering as a global financial crime\n- United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988) was a critical milestone\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones:\n- US Money Laundering Control Act of 1986 formally criminalized money laundering\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989 to develop international AML standards\n- US Patriot Act of 2001 significantly expanded AML regulations post-9/11\n\n4. Global Expansion:\n- Many countries progressively adopted AML regulations\n- International standards emerged requiring financial institutions to implement robust compliance programs\n- Increased focus on preventing terrorist financing\n\n5. Modern Era:\n- Continuous evolution of regulations\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Growing emphasis on cryptocurrency and emerging financial technologies\n\nThe legal framework continues to develop in response to evolving financial crime techniques.",
